				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Just played WoW.<a name="57187"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 17 04 6:20 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Reading your response to my post is reminiscent of the tone of posts on the worldofwarcraft.com forums.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">There are significant differances between classes.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
As you went on to describe, the BASIC playstyle for each class is different (warriors build up rage over the course of multiple battles, rogues build up during a single battle, casters use mana), there is a lack of variety in the class-defining spells.  
<br />

<br />
Let me compare and contrast.  In Everquest, if you are a wizard, you start off with some low-level nukes, then you suddenly get to port, then you get Ice Comet (the first amazing nuke), and then you get to xloc, etc. etc.  You get all kinds of unique class abilities as you level up (bard is even more varied!).  In World of Warcraft, you get a few (indeed very unique) abilities at low level, but then you just get higher versions of these as you level up.  You have no new TYPES of abilities to look forward to.  You address this:
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">As far as nothing to look forward to, yes it appears (to those that are impatient and post rather than read) that there is little to look forward to except increasing abilities of the same type.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
If they cannot put the major waypoints of power in the classes THIS LATE in beta, I have very very little hope for them to add them as &quot;tweaks&quot; later.  This is just bad design.  You can't put in boring stock spells for classes, and then suddenly change the whole design later.  Instead, it seems that their design philosophy is that all casters get a basic set of spells that power up over time -- rather than the EQ model where you always have many completely different spell types at higher levels to look forward to.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Lastly about &quot;uber&quot; equipment. I think getting a double linked tunic (a rare item that drops off of a &quot;boss&quot; mobs) at level 31 is pretty d*mn uber.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
What about before level 31?  That's already several weeks into the game, unless you're a hardcore player (&gt;2 hours a day).  For example, at level 14, there are only 2 or 3 staves I can use due to min level restrictions, and the very best one is only a few points better than the very worst one.  Even if you ignore THAT, it is also true that most items add very little to any stat (even the best items).  +4 stamina?  Oh that's amazing (and I can guarantee that that item won't add to any other stat).  5 armor instead of 4?  Woah, big upgrade.  I see this across the board with items in WoW, and several other people responded to a post I made in the WoW forums agreeing with me.
<br />

<br />
You seem to be in WoW-fanboy mode, and are unwilling to step back to see the amazing shortcomings of the game.  There is no arguing with someone that takes that stance.  I just hope that other readers of my thread will think twice before picking up WoW if they see any of the things I've mentioned as issues as things that would bother them.</span></td>
