				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Just played WoW.<a name="57214"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 17 04 10:47 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>You do not need to have a level 65 (or 64 in my case) in order to have great equipment at lower levels in EQ.  That is because there is a great meta-game, the economy.  The economy in WoW is almost non-existence unless you are maxed.  
<br />

<br />
For example, in EQ, suppose you've never played before.  You start a level 1 warrior.  You easily get up to level 5 in a day or less, and at that point you can collect silks and sell them in the bazaar for good money.  Now you have a few hundred pp, and you can do the buy-low sell-high in the bazaar for a week or so, and by the time you are level 15, you can easily have 1k or 2k, and buy something really great (for your level).
<br />

<br />
This same scenario is absolutely 100% impossible in WoW.  It's as if you're constantly doing newbie quests over and over again.  All the gear you get from quests is just merely adequate for the level you receive it at, and if you buy something at a shop (or if you're really lucky, at the auction), it will be just 1 or 2 points above whatever you quested.
<br />

<br />
The economy meta-game in EQ is important to me, and I think it's a lot of fun.  There is no such thing in WoW.</span></td>
