			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Just played WoW.<a name="57260"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 18 04 6:14 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote"> There is more difference in characters than in EQ, perhaps what you are confusing here is that they are not as dependent on each other as EQ is. </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
I think, more than anything else, this right here points out why WoW will fail, and what made Everquest succeed.  Class Inter-dependecy.  Most people don't log onto a MMO just so they can solo all the time, that's what console RPG's are for.  The log onto them to be around other people, to group with them and hunt with them.  
<br />

<br />
By making all classes pretty much entirely self-reliant, you wipe out the game-reasons behind classes grouping up together to become stronger.  
<br />

<br />
Everquest, as it is today, is actually a really bad example for a &quot;successful&quot; game.  The fact is the games been running on fumes for the past several years, previous success and addiction to the game has kept it going alot more than the poorly designed expansions and changes have.
<br />

<br />
Everquest, as it was originally released and for the first couple expansions however, was what got everyone so hooked in the first place.  Compare that Everquest to WoW and you see where WoW is gonna fail so horrably.  EQ2, being designed by essentially the same company that eventually ruined EQ1(Sony) looks iffy at best.  But that at least is still up in the air.
<br />

<br />
The funny thing about EQ1 is it was all the &quot;mistakes&quot; that Verant made that made it such a wonderful game.  All those things that SoE has been &quot;correcting&quot;, essentially from people whining about one thing or another, has pretty well drained real joy away that the game used to have.</span></td>
