			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Just played WoW.<a name="57282"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 18 04 9:15 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Don't know much about WoW, but I definately have some thoughts about bland items and spells. 
<br />

<br />
I played Horizons for 2 months and I can tell you flat out that the bland scaling of items and spells was plain rediculous.  Boring and uninspiring.  The only difference between a 20 monk and a 100 monk was that he had a linear scaling of equipment.  You could plug in a X = ?Y formula and get about 90% accurate on all upgrades.
<br />

<br />
I'm a pattern kinda guy and the patterns of spells and horizons was rediculously simple.  No major jumps, nothing significant, just simple, linear scaled progress.  
<br />

<br />
I think the asynchronous changes in EQ are part of what makes it interesting.  Sure, some things scale linearly, but some things don't.  Some of that happened as part of a balancing process over the years, rather than brilliant forsight, but it still makes a beautiful non-linear progression of characters.  
<br />

<br />
Take clerics.  Clerics start out with basic heals, just like other healers (though earlier).  Then, at 39 a huge thing changes.  Complete heal.  Now, complete heal is broken, but it doesn't change the fact that all of a sudden the character changes.  Then, somewhere along the way, they pick up their first heal over times.  Then, up in the high 50's, they get their proccing hammers, which adds a completely different dimension to their character. 
<br />

<br />
Bards.  Bards start with some very basic, uninteresting songs.  But, then, they get 39 charm.  And, somewhere along the way, they pick up some good mezzes (now at 17, but it didn't used to be there).  And Invis happens at like 21...  And, in the 60's the spell sets change drastically, making haste and overhaste and such.  At 55 and 65, you get MR debuffs that you didn't have before.  And, eventually, you get your 52% 1 min slow.  
<br />

<br />
The overall effect is that your character changes.  The skills you get, the songs you play makes your character FEEL different.  The way I play my bard now is NOTHING AT ALL like I played my bard at 25.  NOTHING.  Or at 45.  Or even at 55.  It's 100% completely different and barely resembles what I used to do. 
<br />

<br />
Balanced or not, that makes the game interesting.   I have no idea if WoW or EQ2 will pull that off, but I can definately point to Horizons and show you what failure looks like.
<br />

<br />
Wyndaria, 
<br />
Maestro, Nameless.
<br />
</span></td>
