				<td colspan="2"><span>EQOA was quite the same way. Linear development with linear equipment. But they also had quests that gained equipment beyond the normal upgrade pattern(A sort of life long epic, so to speak) and they also incorporated a random drop system where all mobs had a chance to drop a rare item from a treasure class appropriate to their level/location. This made equipment progression very exciting.
<br />

<br />
I had thought, from reading the FAQ and some previews on WoW, that blizzard had done similar things. A basic linear progression in general upgrade with a randomized chance at getting good stuff you'd wear over the next 2-3 upgrades or until you find/quest better.
<br />

<br />
If you think about how EQ started, the basic progression was cloth/patchwork -&gt; banded -&gt; bronze -&gt; fine steel.
<br />

<br />
Fast forward 5 years and now you have GoD mobs dropping stuff that could replace a full suit of fine steel all by itself.
<br />

<br />
I haven't played WoW but if its anything like the original poster described then it just lost a little flavor, for me anyway. But I don't think we can see the entire picture quite yet. While betaing EQOA up until release a LOT of the dungeons and named mobs had not been itemized yet.
<br />

<br />
I still have hope that WoW while live up to its maker's name. </span></td>
