				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">
<br />
If you think about how EQ started, the basic progression was cloth/patchwork -&gt; banded -&gt; bronze -&gt; fine steel. </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
That was going to be my point exactly.  In the very beginning of EQ, you would hunt for cloth, or pelts for patchwork.  Then save up all your money for banded, which was only marginally better than cloth/patchwork.  a few AC per peice better.  Then on to bronze, etc...  
<br />

<br />
You have to realize with a game that is 5 years old, of course equipment and stats are going to be out of this world.  300 hp on one item, if you woudl have told me that 5 years ago I woudl have laughed in your face and said &quot;No way&quot;.  Items with 5 stamina or 5 str were very impressive all the way up to level 35/40.  It wasn't until the upper 40s, or max (read 50) that you could really hunt for and aquire &quot;uber&quot; equipment.
<br />

<br />
In WoW, a game still in beta, they are doing the exact same thing as in early EQ.  Upgrades being only a few AC better, with 1 maybe 2 stat increasing attributes.   I for one am looking forward to playing WoW, mainly because its rich history and story that comes along with, and the fact that players are making this game.  Look at one of the main designers, Tigole.  The old Leader of Legacy of Steel.  I expect when the raid content goes live it will be superb.  If you ever read any of Tigole's ideas or chatted with him personally, he had some excellent ideas, and a mind for encounters.
<br />

<br />
I wouldn't write WoW off yet, give it a chance to actually finish beta, and have the end content found/explored.  I would wager a bet it will be more than enough to look forward to.</span></td>
