				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Just played WoW.<a name="57373"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 18 04 4:10 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Class Inter-dependecy. Most people don't log onto a MMO just so they can solo all the time, that's what console RPG's are for. The log onto them to be around other people, to group with them and hunt with them. 
<br />

<br />
By making all classes pretty much entirely self-reliant, you wipe out the game-reasons behind classes grouping up together to become stronger. </span></blockquote> 
<br />

<br />
Tounces, it would seem that the overlap would instead create more ties between people...of course you can solo the first 5, 6 levels but then it starts becoming group content and you MUST group.
<br />

<br />
On the issue of itemization, though, EQ IS a 5 year old game as Tils put it. At level 50 the uber raid content yielded very little compared to what we have now, and that was the level 50 cap in EQ!
<br />

<br />
As for linear progression, yes it's true that the things bards do at level 65 is quite a bit different from what was done at 55, and 45 is yet again another thing from level 55 and so on. This is a unique case though because most, if not all the rest of the classes, did the same thing they had done before: Enchanters were mezzing and slowing, clerics were healing, warriors, paladins, and shadow knights were tanking at level 25 and still do at level 65. Bards have the advantage in being very versatile overall with quite a curb in playstyles and that's one reason I like to play the bard so much.</span></td>
